
00:00:00,801 --> 00:00:02,002
(man) The sharks are back

00:00:02,002 --> 00:00:04,671
in an all-new season
of "Shark Tank,"

00:00:04,671 --> 00:00:07,374
Where hopeful entrepreneurs
from across the country

00:00:07,374 --> 00:00:10,077
dream of a chance
to secure an investment

00:00:10,077 --> 00:00:12,179
and gain powerful partners

00:00:12,179 --> 00:00:15,449
to start, grow, or save
their businesses.

00:00:15,449 --> 00:00:17,351
If the sharks hear
a great idea,

00:00:17,351 --> 00:00:20,187
they're ready to invest
using their own money...

00:00:20,187 --> 00:00:22,956
mark, would you like
to go in with me?

00:00:22,956 --> 00:00:24,958
You'd be insane
not to take that.

00:00:24,958 --> 00:00:28,028
And they'll fight each other
for a piece of the action.

00:00:28,028 --> 00:00:29,029
I'll give you more cash.

00:00:29,029 --> 00:00:30,564
Did you just jump in
on my geek?

00:00:30,564 --> 00:00:33,901
But first the entrepreneurs
must convince a shark

00:00:33,901 --> 00:00:36,703
to invest the full amount
they're asking for,

00:00:36,703 --> 00:00:38,672
or they'll walk away
with nothing.

00:00:38,672 --> 00:00:40,140
Mama taught me
how to bake.

00:00:40,140 --> 00:00:41,742
This company's gonna be
a lot bigger than $10 million.

00:00:41,742 --> 00:00:42,910
(Robert) Wow.
Wow.

00:00:42,910 --> 00:00:44,244
It's sink...

00:00:44,244 --> 00:00:45,245
you're telling me

00:00:45,245 --> 00:00:46,880
you can't
control your own destiny.

00:00:46,880 --> 00:00:48,448
Or swim...

00:00:48,448 --> 00:00:52,452
this girl served 15 months
in Afghanistan for you.

00:00:52,452 --> 00:00:54,354
So...
wow.

00:00:54,354 --> 00:00:55,889
While you were making money!

00:00:57,057 --> 00:00:59,660
Who are the sharks?

00:00:59,660 --> 00:01:03,564
They're self-made millionaire
and billionaire investors

00:01:03,564 --> 00:01:05,832
who are entrepreneurs
themselves.

00:01:07,234 --> 00:01:09,870
Kevin O'Leary
is a venture capitalist

00:01:09,870 --> 00:01:13,073
who turned a $10,000 loan
into a software business

00:01:13,073 --> 00:01:17,578
worth $4.2 billion.

00:01:17,578 --> 00:01:19,947
Lori Greiner,
the queen of QVC,

00:01:19,947 --> 00:01:21,582
holds over a hundred patents

00:01:21,582 --> 00:01:23,517
and has launched
over 300 products,

00:01:23,517 --> 00:01:25,819
grossing over
a half a billion dollars

00:01:25,819 --> 00:01:27,387
in retail sales.

00:01:27,387 --> 00:01:30,490
Daymond John is a fashion mogul
and branding expert

00:01:30,490 --> 00:01:32,059
who grew his homemade
clothing line

00:01:32,059 --> 00:01:36,597
into the globally recognized
fashion brand fubu.

00:01:36,597 --> 00:01:39,700
Robert Herjavec, the son
of an immigrant factory worker,

00:01:39,700 --> 00:01:41,368
is now a technology mogul

00:01:41,368 --> 00:01:43,203
who sold
his first internet companies

00:01:43,203 --> 00:01:47,007
for over $350 million.

00:01:47,007 --> 00:01:48,875
And Mark Cuban,

00:01:48,875 --> 00:01:51,211
notorious
billionaire entrepreneur

00:01:51,211 --> 00:01:55,100
and the outspoken owner
of the Dallas Mavericks.

00:01:55,100 --> 00:02:05,892
♪♪

00:02:07,160 --> 00:02:09,529
First into the shark tank
is J. Jones,

00:02:09,529 --> 00:02:11,798
an American who believes
he has perfected

00:02:11,798 --> 00:02:15,969
a traditional English Treat.

00:02:15,969 --> 00:02:19,773
Hi, I'm J. Jones
from Denver, Colorado,

00:02:19,773 --> 00:02:22,643
my company is Jones Scones.

00:02:22,643 --> 00:02:25,012
And I'm asking for $100,000

00:02:25,012 --> 00:02:26,680
for 25% of my company.

00:02:26,680 --> 00:02:29,149
Let me tell you
why Jones Scones are awesome--

00:02:29,149 --> 00:02:30,584
It's because they're authentic.

00:02:30,584 --> 00:02:32,719
They're just like the scones
you would find in England,

00:02:32,719 --> 00:02:34,988
and not the cardboard,
icing-covered copies

00:02:34,988 --> 00:02:36,823
that you find
in some coffee chains here.

00:02:36,823 --> 00:02:39,092
Now I started making scones
for the usual reasons,

00:02:39,092 --> 00:02:41,762
and that's pretty much
England and women.

00:02:41,762 --> 00:02:42,996
When I lived in England,

00:02:42,996 --> 00:02:44,798
I was there for school
and some other adventures.

00:02:44,798 --> 00:02:47,167
I fell in love
with my local bakery's scones.

00:02:47,167 --> 00:02:49,202
And when I came home
to go to law school in D.C.,

00:02:49,202 --> 00:02:50,537
I could not find a scone

00:02:50,537 --> 00:02:52,172
that did not taste
like compressed sand.

00:02:52,172 --> 00:02:54,441
So mama taught me how to bake.
I made a scone.

00:02:54,441 --> 00:02:55,942
And I would make them
for friends,

00:02:55,942 --> 00:02:57,377
they helped out
when I was dating.

00:02:57,377 --> 00:02:59,980
So I put my law career on hold
and I dove in headfirst.

00:02:59,980 --> 00:03:01,081
Had no capital.

00:03:01,081 --> 00:03:03,617
I was delivering scones
in my jeep.

00:03:03,617 --> 00:03:06,687
So I have some scones
for you to try.

00:03:09,523 --> 00:03:11,124
Some blueberry.
Blueberry?

00:03:11,124 --> 00:03:12,292
That's blueberry.
Thank you.

00:03:12,292 --> 00:03:14,127
How about you, Lori?
What do you want?

00:03:14,127 --> 00:03:16,763
All right. I'm a chocolate girl.
Is there a chocolate?
Oh, yes. Oh, yes.

00:03:16,763 --> 00:03:17,964
Thank you.
Is that blueberry up there?

00:03:17,964 --> 00:03:19,132
It's blueberry.
Hey, save me a blueberry.

00:03:19,132 --> 00:03:20,367
You want a blueberry?
Yes, sir.

00:03:20,367 --> 00:03:21,768
Mark, you can share
half mine.

00:03:21,768 --> 00:03:24,104
That's what's up right there.

00:03:24,104 --> 00:03:25,839
(Robert)
J., why is it so dry?

00:03:25,839 --> 00:03:27,607
Is that on purpose?

00:03:27,607 --> 00:03:29,676
Our scones
tend to be more moist.

00:03:29,676 --> 00:03:30,944
If you're experiencing
a dryness,

00:03:30,944 --> 00:03:32,312
I find that
to be unusual.

00:03:32,312 --> 00:03:34,081
Scones are on
the drier side.

00:03:34,081 --> 00:03:36,717
They're not like
a muffin. More like a biscuit.

00:03:36,717 --> 00:03:39,319
Are scones typically
a breakfast food?
Yes.

00:03:39,319 --> 00:03:40,487
They are.

00:03:40,487 --> 00:03:41,922
J., what are you selling
in terms of the scone?

00:03:41,922 --> 00:03:45,258
Are the... are the scones
selling cash?

00:03:45,258 --> 00:03:47,461
Yes. Uh...
how much?

00:03:47,461 --> 00:03:50,397
We are selling right now
$5,000 worth of scones a month.

00:03:50,397 --> 00:03:51,565
(Lori) a month.
A month.

00:03:51,565 --> 00:03:52,733
Yes.

00:03:52,733 --> 00:03:53,900
Why are your scones better

00:03:53,900 --> 00:03:56,069
than the other
typical scones?

00:03:56,069 --> 00:03:57,170
Well, number one,

00:03:57,170 --> 00:03:58,872
that cream style
that we talked about.

00:03:58,872 --> 00:04:00,006
Number two,
they're all natural.

00:04:00,006 --> 00:04:03,343
So we found a home
in Whole Foods.

00:04:03,343 --> 00:04:04,344
You're in Whole Foods?

00:04:04,344 --> 00:04:05,445
One store, right?

00:04:05,445 --> 00:04:06,613
(laughs) No.

00:04:06,613 --> 00:04:08,014
We're in--We're in
six stores now,

00:04:08,014 --> 00:04:09,683
uh, in the Denver/
Rocky mountain region,

00:04:09,683 --> 00:04:10,717
and in Utah.

00:04:10,717 --> 00:04:12,385
Why can't you get
all the stores?

00:04:12,385 --> 00:04:15,689
We were. And, uh, might as well
kick into the sales talk.

00:04:15,689 --> 00:04:16,823
At one point,
we were selling

00:04:16,823 --> 00:04:18,692
$113,000 worth of scones
a month.

00:04:18,692 --> 00:04:20,293
We sold
a half-million of these

00:04:20,293 --> 00:04:22,662
over the course
of the life of the business.
What happened, J.?

00:04:22,662 --> 00:04:25,632
Well, uh... (laughs)
This is why we're here.
This is not good.

00:04:25,632 --> 00:04:27,067
Is this a bad story?

00:04:27,067 --> 00:04:29,202
No, it's not a bad story,
'cause I'm here.

00:04:29,202 --> 00:04:30,203
All right. Tell us.

00:04:30,203 --> 00:04:31,738
What we did was,
we expanded.

00:04:31,738 --> 00:04:34,741
We went from Denver
out to California,

00:04:34,741 --> 00:04:36,977
and we picked
a new manufacturer.

00:04:36,977 --> 00:04:38,044
Terrible mistake.

00:04:38,044 --> 00:04:40,580
I was not able
to oversee my co-packing

00:04:40,580 --> 00:04:41,748
the way I should have.

00:04:41,748 --> 00:04:43,049
And when I had to correct
that mistake,

00:04:43,049 --> 00:04:44,651
we didn't have
the capital to fix it.

00:04:44,651 --> 00:04:45,919
We had to pull back,

00:04:45,919 --> 00:04:48,688
so sales came back down
to $75,000 last year--

00:04:48,688 --> 00:04:50,824
Or 2 years ago,
and $65,000.

00:04:50,824 --> 00:04:52,259
So they didn't manufacture
good product for you,

00:04:52,259 --> 00:04:53,627
was that the problem?

00:04:53,627 --> 00:04:55,328
They didn't do it right.
You couldn't oversee it,

00:04:55,328 --> 00:04:57,130
so you couldn't
come in and test it...
it's not their fault.

00:04:57,130 --> 00:04:58,698
It's my fault. I should have
been out there more

00:04:58,698 --> 00:05:00,100
to watch the product.

00:05:00,100 --> 00:05:02,068
And frankly, I should have
been talking to people like you

00:05:02,068 --> 00:05:04,104
before I expanded, because
we would have had the capital

00:05:04,104 --> 00:05:07,641
to maintain the ground
that I worked so hard to earn.

00:05:07,641 --> 00:05:09,643
Are those same stores now

00:05:09,643 --> 00:05:11,478
willing to give you
another chance?

00:05:11,478 --> 00:05:12,779
Yes. We know that in Denver,

00:05:12,779 --> 00:05:14,548
and we believe so
in California.

00:05:14,548 --> 00:05:17,050
How long have you been
in the Denver Whole Foods,

00:05:17,050 --> 00:05:18,718
and how many times
have they reordered?

00:05:18,718 --> 00:05:19,886
Seven years.

00:05:19,886 --> 00:05:21,688
Seven years?
(Robert) seven years?

00:05:21,688 --> 00:05:24,524
Yeah.
We went from selling

00:05:24,524 --> 00:05:28,361
$37,000 worth of scones
in '07

00:05:28,361 --> 00:05:31,364
to selling $60,500
in '08

00:05:31,364 --> 00:05:34,234
to selling $113,000
in 2009.

00:05:34,234 --> 00:05:37,437
I'm just--I'm not
a big scone guy.

00:05:37,437 --> 00:05:39,005
I could tell. (laughs)

00:05:39,005 --> 00:05:41,007
Um, but when I
walk into a whole foods today,

00:05:41,007 --> 00:05:43,510
do I see
only Jones Scones

00:05:43,510 --> 00:05:46,880
or do I see multiple
manufacturers of scones?

00:05:46,880 --> 00:05:48,615
People have
done scones locally.

00:05:48,615 --> 00:05:50,417
Nobody has gone
into the scones category

00:05:50,417 --> 00:05:51,952
and said, "Hi, I'm Jones."

00:05:51,952 --> 00:05:53,653
We've got a brand. We've got
someone you can attach it to.

00:05:53,653 --> 00:05:54,955
So it's a fragmented market.

00:05:54,955 --> 00:05:57,390
You're trying
to become the brand.

00:05:57,390 --> 00:05:59,259
Absolutely.
Yeah, but after six,
seven years

00:05:59,259 --> 00:06:03,630
of around $60,000,
one year popped to $130,000...

00:06:03,630 --> 00:06:07,968
what will $100,000 do that
will be so magical this year?

00:06:07,968 --> 00:06:10,337
We are going to
hire food brokers,

00:06:10,337 --> 00:06:12,505
which is the way to get
our sales force out there.

00:06:12,505 --> 00:06:16,776
The biggest cost that we have
is feeding people the scones.

00:06:16,776 --> 00:06:19,713
You know what, man? J.,
you are such a likeable person.

00:06:19,713 --> 00:06:22,349
Um, I just don't like it.

00:06:22,349 --> 00:06:24,384
Well, let me continue
on--on how...

00:06:24,384 --> 00:06:25,752
you don't
have to with me. I like...

00:06:25,752 --> 00:06:28,288
I like you, but...

00:06:28,288 --> 00:06:29,456
I'm out.

00:06:29,456 --> 00:06:31,825
Okay.

00:06:31,825 --> 00:06:34,594
We looked at what we can sell
the scones for.

00:06:34,594 --> 00:06:35,629
Whole foods, actually,

00:06:35,629 --> 00:06:38,031
each store Sells
$368 worth of scones

00:06:38,031 --> 00:06:39,833
selling 12 cases a month.

00:06:39,833 --> 00:06:41,067
That says we're gonna have

00:06:41,067 --> 00:06:43,136
about a quarter of
a million dollars in sales.

00:06:43,136 --> 00:06:45,805
Potential. But here's
the reality that I see--

00:06:45,805 --> 00:06:47,841
You've been in business
for ten years.

00:06:47,841 --> 00:06:51,244
Your sales in the last three
have actually declined.

00:06:51,244 --> 00:06:53,246
Lots of potential.

00:06:53,246 --> 00:06:56,383
Tell me what you've learned
in the last few years

00:06:56,383 --> 00:06:58,585
that when you wake up tomorrow,

00:06:58,585 --> 00:07:02,088
it's gonna be a different day
than it was in the past.

00:07:02,088 --> 00:07:04,991
Team. That's the next part.
Team.

00:07:04,991 --> 00:07:08,261
I've got a guy that can guide me
with what I'm doing.

00:07:08,261 --> 00:07:09,262
That's bull crap.

00:07:09,262 --> 00:07:11,031
What you're telling me,

00:07:11,031 --> 00:07:14,334
without any uncertainty
whatsoever,

00:07:14,334 --> 00:07:16,770
is you can't control
your own destiny.

00:07:16,770 --> 00:07:18,171
I-I hate to agree with Mark,

00:07:18,171 --> 00:07:19,606
but I agree with him 100%.

00:07:19,606 --> 00:07:22,876
You're looking for answers
from people outside of yourself.

00:07:22,876 --> 00:07:24,544
I hate when people
tell me

00:07:24,544 --> 00:07:27,580
the answer to my salvation
is a consultant.

00:07:27,580 --> 00:07:29,015
Yeah. No kidding.

00:07:29,015 --> 00:07:30,984
No, I'm--I'm not
looking for a consultant, guys.

00:07:30,984 --> 00:07:32,218
But you are.
That's what you just said.

00:07:32,218 --> 00:07:34,054
Wait, no, he just said
his "Team." His "Team."

00:07:34,054 --> 00:07:35,522
But every one of you
has a team.

00:07:35,522 --> 00:07:37,824
Every one of you
has somebody that you rely on.

00:07:37,824 --> 00:07:39,693
But now you make
the final decisions.

00:07:39,693 --> 00:07:40,860
Here's the thing, though--

00:07:40,860 --> 00:07:42,228
When I hear you say

00:07:42,228 --> 00:07:44,130
that you've been ten years
in the business,

00:07:44,130 --> 00:07:46,032
and you're where
you are right now,

00:07:46,032 --> 00:07:47,734
needing
to ask us for money,

00:07:47,734 --> 00:07:49,402
it tells me
something's wrong.

00:07:49,402 --> 00:07:52,072
There's some reason
why this isn't taking off.

00:07:52,072 --> 00:07:56,376
I'm not sure what that is.
I thought the scone was fine.

00:07:56,376 --> 00:07:58,778
But for me,
I need to love the product

00:07:58,778 --> 00:08:01,247
and feel passionate
and want to eat it constantly.

00:08:01,247 --> 00:08:02,983
And I'm not at that place.

00:08:02,983 --> 00:08:05,919
So for that reason,
I'm out.

00:08:05,919 --> 00:08:08,054
Sorry to hear that.

00:08:08,054 --> 00:08:09,489
What else
can I answer for you?

00:08:09,489 --> 00:08:11,958
How can--How can
I bring us closer?

00:08:11,958 --> 00:08:13,927
Well, J.,
here's how I see it--

00:08:13,927 --> 00:08:14,928
I agree with you.

00:08:14,928 --> 00:08:16,963
Nobody wins without a team.

00:08:16,963 --> 00:08:20,767
But I don't have time to be
part of that overall team.

00:08:20,767 --> 00:08:23,870
I wish you all the best,
'cause you're a very nice guy.

00:08:23,870 --> 00:08:26,072
But I'm out.

00:08:26,072 --> 00:08:28,808
Mr. Wonderful?

00:08:32,112 --> 00:08:33,780
You know, I don't get
emotionally involved.

00:08:33,780 --> 00:08:37,817
The scones are good.
I eat scones.

00:08:37,817 --> 00:08:40,653
But there's nothing proprietary
about making a scone.

00:08:40,653 --> 00:08:43,590
All there is
is executional excellence.

00:08:43,590 --> 00:08:47,460
And on that test,
you failed once.

00:08:47,460 --> 00:08:50,397
Doesn't mean
you can't recover.

00:08:50,397 --> 00:08:52,298
But cutting your sales in half

00:08:52,298 --> 00:08:55,835
in a commodity business
like scones is never good.

00:08:57,103 --> 00:09:01,341
Look, this is about money.

00:09:01,341 --> 00:09:04,377
And I can't make any
from what I see. I'm out.

00:09:04,377 --> 00:09:07,747
Well, I have to thank you
for your time.

00:09:07,747 --> 00:09:09,049
Good luck.

00:09:09,049 --> 00:09:10,383
Good luck.
Cheers.

00:09:12,052 --> 00:09:14,087
And I'm out. (chuckles)

00:09:15,989 --> 00:09:17,757
Mark never said
he's out?

00:09:17,757 --> 00:09:19,125
Mark never said
he was out? (laughs)
I gave him a little quickie.

00:09:19,125 --> 00:09:20,126
I gave him
a little quickie.

00:09:20,126 --> 00:09:21,828
(laughing) That's a first.

00:09:21,828 --> 00:09:23,563
Bye. (laughs)

00:09:23,563 --> 00:09:25,398
He gave up.

00:09:25,398 --> 00:09:27,067
Something new every day.

00:09:27,067 --> 00:09:28,668
Oh, my goodness.

00:09:28,668 --> 00:09:31,805
♪♪

00:09:36,743 --> 00:09:37,944
♪♪

00:09:37,944 --> 00:09:40,280
Next up is Brian Altomare,

00:09:40,280 --> 00:09:42,949
whose business aims
to help people

00:09:42,949 --> 00:09:44,651
with their extra baggage.

00:09:53,433 --> 00:09:55,835
Hi. My name is Brian Altomare,
and I'm from New York.

00:09:55,835 --> 00:09:57,904
My company is Lugless,

00:09:57,904 --> 00:09:59,806
and I'm here asking
for $100,000

00:09:59,806 --> 00:10:01,541
for 10% equity.

00:10:01,541 --> 00:10:03,610
Sharks,
people are tired of paying

00:10:03,610 --> 00:10:05,111
ridiculous airline baggage fees,

00:10:05,111 --> 00:10:06,746
tired of lost luggage,

00:10:06,746 --> 00:10:09,449
and tired of T.S.A.
pilfering through their luggage.

00:10:09,449 --> 00:10:11,150
So are we.

00:10:11,150 --> 00:10:13,386
That's why we've solved
these problems forever.

00:10:13,386 --> 00:10:15,355
Introducing Lugless--

00:10:15,355 --> 00:10:17,223
A door-to-door
luggage shipping service

00:10:17,223 --> 00:10:20,860
that picks up your luggage
from your home, office, or hotel

00:10:20,860 --> 00:10:23,596
and sends it to wherever
you're going ahead of time.

00:10:23,596 --> 00:10:24,764
And when your trip is over,

00:10:24,764 --> 00:10:25,932
we'll pick your luggage
right back up

00:10:25,932 --> 00:10:27,300
and send it on home for you.

00:10:27,300 --> 00:10:29,402
We send luggage
to over 200 countries

