00:20:00,180 --> 00:20:02,449
action figures,
even comic books

00:20:02,449 --> 00:20:04,184
are bought mostly by adults.

00:20:04,184 --> 00:20:05,967
(sighs deeply)
So...

00:20:05,967 --> 00:20:06,767
(laughs)

00:20:06,767 --> 00:20:08,300
My wife tolerated my games
on the dining table,

00:20:08,300 --> 00:20:10,402
my controllers in baskets
on the coffee table,

00:20:10,402 --> 00:20:12,271
and, uh, white cardboard boxes

00:20:12,271 --> 00:20:14,506
invading our lives
on comic wednesdays.

00:20:14,506 --> 00:20:16,508
But I could see
that it aggravated her,

00:20:16,508 --> 00:20:18,977
and in a rare moment
of marital insight...

00:20:18,977 --> 00:20:21,513
(bell chimes)
I realized
that she deserved better.

00:20:21,513 --> 00:20:24,750
So I started designing
beautiful, geeky furniture

00:20:24,750 --> 00:20:26,585
that would be at home
in our home.

00:20:26,585 --> 00:20:28,253
But then I had
a more startling revelation--

00:20:28,253 --> 00:20:30,122
that we all deserve better.

00:20:30,122 --> 00:20:32,458
Well, and that's where
geek chic comes in.

00:20:32,458 --> 00:20:36,328
This is a black walnut
3X5 emissary dining table,

00:20:36,328 --> 00:20:39,498
but like many good things geek,
it's more than meets the eye.

00:20:39,498 --> 00:20:42,334
So if I reach back
down here,

00:20:42,334 --> 00:20:45,738
with the push of a button,
I reveal a second surface.

00:20:48,373 --> 00:20:50,943
This surface can be used
for card games

00:20:50,943 --> 00:20:53,645
or board games
or anything you want to do,

00:20:53,645 --> 00:20:54,980
in progress or in storage.

00:20:54,980 --> 00:20:56,315
If I pull out of this drawer,

00:20:56,315 --> 00:20:57,783
it becomes a desk,

00:20:57,783 --> 00:21:00,753
and the desk
is good for laptops

00:21:00,753 --> 00:21:03,322
or for running
a role-playing game.

00:21:03,322 --> 00:21:04,990
We also have this rail

00:21:04,990 --> 00:21:07,626
that we can attach accessories
like bins

00:21:07,626 --> 00:21:09,495
and counter holders,

00:21:09,495 --> 00:21:11,430
and even wineglass holders.

00:21:11,430 --> 00:21:13,265
(snaps)

00:21:13,265 --> 00:21:16,702
the configuration
just opens up.

00:21:16,702 --> 00:21:19,538
Geeks, by accident or design,
are shaping the world,

00:21:19,538 --> 00:21:21,039
and Geek Chic is the brand

00:21:21,039 --> 00:21:24,009
that's going to design
and shape it with them.

00:21:24,009 --> 00:21:25,677
So, sharks,

00:21:25,677 --> 00:21:27,479
and hopefully geeks,

00:21:27,479 --> 00:21:30,582
what do you need to know
to become a part of geek chic?

00:21:30,582 --> 00:21:32,017
(laughs)

00:21:32,017 --> 00:21:34,153
Is this your only product
or do you have more products?

00:21:34,153 --> 00:21:35,387
No, no, we have--

00:21:35,387 --> 00:21:36,889
This is one of, uh,
19 pieces of furniture

00:21:36,889 --> 00:21:38,423
that we currently offer.

00:21:38,423 --> 00:21:39,758
(Robert) Can I see it?
(Lori) Yeah, I was gonna say--

00:21:39,758 --> 00:21:41,093
So they're all tables
and cabinets at the moment,

00:21:41,093 --> 00:21:42,394
or are there also chairs or--

00:21:42,394 --> 00:21:44,663
We do chairs as well,
absolutely.

00:21:44,663 --> 00:21:46,431
Oh, this is really cool.

00:21:46,431 --> 00:21:48,433
And this is the desk?
Yep.

00:21:48,433 --> 00:21:50,068
Wow. Very clever.

00:21:50,068 --> 00:21:52,070
Do you customize them,
what's inside here?

00:21:52,070 --> 00:21:54,740
So it could be a poker table,
it could be a crap table,

00:21:54,740 --> 00:21:55,941
it could be...
right.

00:21:55,941 --> 00:21:57,376
Whatever you decide to order?

00:21:57,376 --> 00:21:58,777
Yeah, absolutely.

00:21:58,777 --> 00:22:00,179
That's what--You're seeing
two examples there.

00:22:00,179 --> 00:22:01,713
There's a wet-dry-erase surface
that's over,

00:22:01,713 --> 00:22:03,549
uh, one of our maps.
(Robert) Oh, look at this.

00:22:03,549 --> 00:22:04,883
That thing--
Yeah, that just comes out.

00:22:04,883 --> 00:22:06,385
That would be--you could have
that full inset

00:22:06,385 --> 00:22:08,320
for playing cards on.

00:22:08,320 --> 00:22:09,521
What does this cost?

00:22:09,521 --> 00:22:10,923
Uh, about $3,500,
I would say.

00:22:10,923 --> 00:22:12,090
Wow, that's reasonable...
Mm-hmm.

00:22:12,090 --> 00:22:13,258
For this quality.

00:22:13,258 --> 00:22:14,426
How many sales do you have?

00:22:14,426 --> 00:22:16,962
We did $2 million
in sales last year.

00:22:16,962 --> 00:22:18,997
Wow.
Th--Yes.

00:22:18,997 --> 00:22:20,098
Impressive.

00:22:20,098 --> 00:22:21,633
What was your profit?

00:22:21,633 --> 00:22:22,901
We were negative.

00:22:22,901 --> 00:22:24,169
We were in the red by $100,000
on $2 million.

00:22:24,169 --> 00:22:26,405
Whoa.

00:22:26,405 --> 00:22:29,208
We know what furniture
manufacturers are worth.

00:22:29,208 --> 00:22:31,910
5 times free cash.

00:22:31,910 --> 00:22:33,712
Sure.
You don't have any free cash.

00:22:33,712 --> 00:22:35,781
Why are you worth $2 million?

00:22:35,781 --> 00:22:38,584
I'm worth more
than $2 million.

00:22:38,584 --> 00:22:42,421
The $2 million is what we did
in revenue last fiscal year.

00:22:42,421 --> 00:22:44,790
So what are your projected
cash flows for this year?

00:22:44,790 --> 00:22:48,393
Um, I believe that our projected
is about $400,000 or $500,000.

00:22:48,393 --> 00:22:51,330
And what are you gonna use
the $100,000 from us for?

00:22:51,330 --> 00:22:53,232
Well, I'm gonna use it
to probably buy a truck

00:22:53,232 --> 00:22:54,967
to expand
our shipping operations

00:22:54,967 --> 00:22:57,035
and probably put on--
Get some more machinery

00:22:57,035 --> 00:22:59,972
in the facility
to increase our efficiencies.

00:22:59,972 --> 00:23:01,473
What is your average order?

00:23:01,473 --> 00:23:04,543
Uh, our average order's about
$4,000, $4,500.

00:23:04,543 --> 00:23:06,712
So how much are your margins,
then, on that table?

00:23:06,712 --> 00:23:09,915
Uh, about--Well, this is about
$1,800 to make a $3,500 table.

00:23:09,915 --> 00:23:12,017
So about 50%?
Yes.

00:23:12,017 --> 00:23:13,185
The furniture manufacturing
sector

00:23:13,185 --> 00:23:14,519
has been decimated in America.

00:23:14,519 --> 00:23:16,154
Yes.
It's all in Asia now.

00:23:16,154 --> 00:23:19,758
Why are you staying alive?
Why are you not a dead geek?

00:23:19,758 --> 00:23:21,827
Because I am not trying
to compete with China.

00:23:21,827 --> 00:23:24,263
China does what they do
very, very well.

00:23:24,263 --> 00:23:25,464
But they aren't gonna
be able to make

00:23:25,464 --> 00:23:26,965
North American
fully hardwood furniture

00:23:26,965 --> 00:23:28,934
in the same kind of way
at a competitive level.

00:23:28,934 --> 00:23:30,235
They can't do that.

00:23:31,570 --> 00:23:33,605
(Lori)
I-I think you're great.

00:23:33,605 --> 00:23:35,107
I love your enthusiasm.

00:23:35,107 --> 00:23:37,809
This is a beautiful table,
really beautiful.

00:23:37,809 --> 00:23:40,545
I've seen
a lot of tables similar.

00:23:40,545 --> 00:23:41,880
I'm just not sure
how you're gonna get

00:23:41,880 --> 00:23:43,548
the competitive edge
on top of them

00:23:43,548 --> 00:23:45,984
because some of them
are very high-end.

00:23:45,984 --> 00:23:49,221
So for that reason,
I'm out.

00:23:49,221 --> 00:23:50,722
Okay.

00:23:50,722 --> 00:23:53,492
Robert, do you want to sell this
to a lot of people

00:23:53,492 --> 00:23:57,329
or do you want to stay
very niche-oriented,

00:23:57,329 --> 00:24:00,999
make very high-end stuff,
maybe grow to $10 million,

00:24:00,999 --> 00:24:03,001
and just keep it at that?

00:24:03,001 --> 00:24:04,503
This company's gonna be
a lot bigger than $10 million.

00:24:04,503 --> 00:24:06,705
And we--I want to sell it
to a lot more than--

00:24:06,705 --> 00:24:08,106
Than just geeks.

00:24:08,106 --> 00:24:09,608
Everyone's looking at this
and going,

00:24:09,608 --> 00:24:11,944
"Man, that is nice.
I really do want--I want that.

00:24:11,944 --> 00:24:13,278
That's something"--

00:24:13,278 --> 00:24:14,613
see, that--That's where
I disconnect, Robert.

00:24:14,613 --> 00:24:17,049
I look at that and say,
"That's a table," you know?

00:24:17,049 --> 00:24:19,351
I don't--I don't see
anything more there.

00:24:19,351 --> 00:24:20,852
Do you see the functionality,
though? Do you see it, Mark?

00:24:20,852 --> 00:24:22,187
Do you see that--that--
That's the part--

00:24:22,187 --> 00:24:23,689
that part of this is,
is about describing

00:24:23,689 --> 00:24:25,424
very specific function
for people?

00:24:25,424 --> 00:24:27,159
I mean, I see
what you're trying--Look...
this may not be for you--

00:24:27,159 --> 00:24:28,460
for me to get into a business,

00:24:28,460 --> 00:24:30,629
I've gotta be relentless
and dive in.

00:24:30,629 --> 00:24:32,130
This sounds like you're
trailing down to "No, sir."

00:24:32,130 --> 00:24:33,632
Yeah, I'm just telling you...
think about it for a second.

00:24:33,632 --> 00:24:35,867
If--if it was Geek Chic
in another direction...
I--this--

00:24:35,867 --> 00:24:37,569
but furniture?

00:24:37,569 --> 00:24:38,737
I'm--That's just not me.

00:24:38,737 --> 00:24:39,905
I--geek furniture is
the beginning

00:24:39,905 --> 00:24:41,340
of what we're doing.

00:24:41,340 --> 00:24:42,507
It is absolutely the beginning
of what we're doing.

00:24:42,507 --> 00:24:44,476
Well, when you get
to the rest of it...

00:24:44,476 --> 00:24:46,311
give you a call?
Give me a call,
but I'm out.

00:24:46,311 --> 00:24:47,612
Fair enough. Fair enough.

00:24:47,612 --> 00:24:49,614
Robert, let me, uh,

00:24:49,614 --> 00:24:52,517
let--Let me tell you where
I differ with your vision...

00:24:52,517 --> 00:24:55,887
that you want to be
a big furniture guy.

00:24:55,887 --> 00:24:57,155
I don't want to be
a big furniture guy.

00:24:57,155 --> 00:24:58,390
I want to be
a big company.

00:24:58,390 --> 00:25:00,659
I buy into the design,
but I don't buy into

00:25:00,659 --> 00:25:02,227
the furniture company
part of it.

00:25:02,227 --> 00:25:03,362
I'm out.

00:25:03,362 --> 00:25:05,364
Okay.

00:25:05,364 --> 00:25:07,566
I have a story
about biology class...
(laughs)

00:25:07,566 --> 00:25:09,468
That may be relevant to this.
(laughs)

00:25:09,468 --> 00:25:10,736
okay.

00:25:10,736 --> 00:25:12,070
I remember once
counting fruit flies

00:25:12,070 --> 00:25:13,572
in a petri dish
with a microscope.

00:25:13,572 --> 00:25:14,940
(laughs) I can't
picture that.

00:25:14,940 --> 00:25:17,209
And after doing about
a hundred of them

00:25:17,209 --> 00:25:18,810
with my little tweezer,
I found one that was not black.

00:25:18,810 --> 00:25:21,079
It was white.
It was clear white.

00:25:21,079 --> 00:25:23,548
And I held it up
for the teacher and I said,

00:25:23,548 --> 00:25:25,684
"What is this doing with
the rest of my fruit flies?"

00:25:25,684 --> 00:25:28,987
and he said,
"That's an anomaly."

00:25:28,987 --> 00:25:30,589
You're that fruit fly.

00:25:30,589 --> 00:25:31,757
You're the anomaly.

00:25:31,757 --> 00:25:34,726
You're in
a really crappy business,

00:25:34,726 --> 00:25:37,129
who got decimated over
the last 20 years in America.

00:25:37,129 --> 00:25:38,463
But if you try and become
a furniture company,

00:25:38,463 --> 00:25:39,798
You'll be like
all the other fruit flies--

00:25:39,798 --> 00:25:40,966
Dead in the petri dish.

00:25:40,966 --> 00:25:42,167
That's what I believe.

00:25:42,167 --> 00:25:43,668
I don't think you should
raise any money

00:25:43,668 --> 00:25:45,570
or give up any equity.

00:25:45,570 --> 00:25:47,906
You should just be
a happy fruit fly.

00:25:47,906 --> 00:25:49,174
I'm out.

00:25:49,174 --> 00:25:52,110
Okay.

00:25:52,110 --> 00:25:53,478
Four sharks are out.

00:25:53,478 --> 00:25:55,847
Oh, yes, Daymond.

00:25:55,847 --> 00:25:58,750
I just don't know if we're
gonna have the same vision.

00:25:58,750 --> 00:26:00,085
If you do this geek angle,

00:26:00,085 --> 00:26:02,521
I just don't know
if I can ride with that.

00:26:02,521 --> 00:26:04,489
But I real--I'm in love
with the stuff,

00:26:04,489 --> 00:26:07,259
and I'm--I'm in love with how
you're running the company.

00:26:09,227 --> 00:26:11,596
You asked for $100,000
for 5%?

00:26:11,596 --> 00:26:13,465
You're right.

00:26:13,465 --> 00:26:16,435
I'm giving you an offer
of $200,000... (exhales)

00:26:16,435 --> 00:26:18,203
for 25%.

00:26:18,203 --> 00:26:23,041
Now I-I mostly made the offer
at $100,000 for 5%

00:26:23,041 --> 00:26:24,976
because I was, you know,
counting the value

00:26:24,976 --> 00:26:28,814
that any shark could bring
to my business, for sure.

00:26:28,814 --> 00:26:31,683
Uh, how about...

00:26:31,683 --> 00:26:35,620
uh, $500,000 for 15%?

00:26:35,620 --> 00:26:37,355
(Robert) So, Robert,
you're raising your value.

00:26:37,355 --> 00:26:39,858
You've gone from
$2-Million value on the company

00:26:39,858 --> 00:26:41,326
to 3.3.

00:26:41,326 --> 00:26:43,495
Yes, and I still think that
that's probably undervalued.

00:26:43,495 --> 00:26:45,664
Now I'm finding a flaw
in your character.

00:26:45,664 --> 00:26:48,100
You see, you came in here
and you offered that--

00:26:48,100 --> 00:26:49,868
not a flaw in my character,
sir.

00:26:49,868 --> 00:26:52,404
Robert, hang on a sec.
Are you considering his offer?

00:26:52,404 --> 00:26:55,006
No. No, I'm--I'm--
I'm countering with a diff--

00:26:55,006 --> 00:26:56,875
All right. I'm gonna have to
stay firm on that offer.

00:26:56,875 --> 00:26:58,844
My ticket to enter

00:26:58,844 --> 00:27:02,681
is my time and $200,000
and 25%.

00:27:02,681 --> 00:27:06,518
Uh, 25%--It's--
25% is Still too high.

00:27:06,518 --> 00:27:08,353
Yeah, then it comes down
to a "Yes" Or "No," Robert.

00:27:08,353 --> 00:27:09,521
We're great partners, man.

00:27:09,521 --> 00:27:12,457
You're 75%. I'm 25%.

00:27:14,593 --> 00:27:16,228
Be true to yourself.

00:27:19,197 --> 00:27:20,432
Robert, I'll give you
more cash.

00:27:22,234 --> 00:27:25,837
♪♪

00:27:31,500 --> 00:27:34,033
Four sharks are out.

00:27:34,033 --> 00:27:36,736
Daymond's made an offer
of $200,000

00:27:36,736 --> 00:27:38,471
for a 25% stake.

00:27:38,471 --> 00:27:40,473
But Robert may have had
a change of heart.

00:27:40,473 --> 00:27:42,208
Robert, I'll give you
more cash.

00:27:45,010 --> 00:27:47,546
I'll give you $300,000
for 25%.

00:27:49,615 --> 00:27:51,217
My vision
is slightly different.

00:27:51,217 --> 00:27:53,753
I gotta tell you, when you have
something beautiful and rare,

00:27:53,753 --> 00:27:55,488
you can charge more for it.

00:27:55,488 --> 00:27:57,523
Did you just jump in
on my geek?

00:27:57,523 --> 00:27:59,058
I sure did.
He did.

00:27:59,058 --> 00:28:01,427
(Kevin) Well, let's summarize
what you've got here.

00:28:01,427 --> 00:28:05,030
Daymond made you an offer
of $200,000 for 25%,

00:28:05,030 --> 00:28:08,400
valuing your company
at $800,000.

00:28:08,400 --> 00:28:10,503
And while you were whining
about that,

00:28:10,503 --> 00:28:14,573
Robert made you an offer
for $300,000 for 25%,

00:28:14,573 --> 00:28:17,910
valuing your company now
at $1.2 million.

00:28:17,910 --> 00:28:20,146
Pee-Wee the fruit fly,
what are you gonna do?

00:28:20,146 --> 00:28:21,480
Could you--could you bring
your offer up

00:28:21,480 --> 00:28:23,382
to match--To match
Robert's offer at this point?

00:28:23,382 --> 00:28:25,384
I cannot, because my time
is worth...

00:28:25,384 --> 00:28:26,986
because your time is--

00:28:26,986 --> 00:28:28,988
I-I--that's fair.
That's completely fair.

00:28:28,988 --> 00:28:31,157
Uh, so..

00:28:31,157 --> 00:28:33,759
I'm s--Thank you, Daymond.
Really, I appreciate

00:28:33,759 --> 00:28:35,694
what you're-- what you're doing--
You taking out
the buzz saw now?

00:28:35,694 --> 00:28:36,962
You want 25% of my company,

00:28:36,962 --> 00:28:38,731
but then again, you said
you don't get geek,

00:28:38,731 --> 00:28:40,266
and you don't
really understand it...
yes.

00:28:40,266 --> 00:28:41,600
And that--And I think that's
probably not--

00:28:41,600 --> 00:28:43,102
That's probably not
a good fit.

00:28:43,102 --> 00:28:44,503
I told you, our vision
may not be on course.

00:28:44,503 --> 00:28:45,971
That's a decision
you have to make.

00:28:45,971 --> 00:28:48,107
I think maybe that's--That's
probably not a good idea.

00:28:49,375 --> 00:28:52,378
Robert, um...
I thought you were out.

00:28:52,378 --> 00:28:53,712
That's the beauty
of the shark tank.

00:28:53,712 --> 00:28:55,080
Anything can change.

00:28:58,184 --> 00:29:00,820
Robert,

00:29:00,820 --> 00:29:02,421
I'd like to accept
your offer.

00:29:02,421 --> 00:29:03,589
Let's do this. We're gonna
make a lot of money.

00:29:03,589 --> 00:29:04,757
You got a deal.

00:29:04,757 --> 00:29:05,925
We're gonna make
a lot of money.

00:29:05,925 --> 00:29:07,092
We sure are.
Thank you, Robert.

00:29:07,092 --> 00:29:08,961
Beautiful. Thank you.
Thank you.

00:29:08,961 --> 00:29:10,830
You just partnered
with a termite.

00:29:10,830 --> 00:29:12,164
Hey, listen, listen...
(sharks laughing)

00:29:12,164 --> 00:29:13,332
He's gonna be good for me.

00:29:13,332 --> 00:29:14,767
You could've been
good for me, too.

00:29:14,767 --> 00:29:17,269
♪♪

00:29:17,269 --> 00:29:19,205
The fruit fly and the termite.

00:29:19,205 --> 00:29:20,873
(Lori and Robert laugh)

00:29:20,873 --> 00:29:22,274
It's a fable.

00:29:22,274 --> 00:29:23,609
I think you definitely suck,
Robert.

00:29:23,609 --> 00:29:25,110
You stole that one from me.

00:29:25,110 --> 00:29:27,313
Oh, I feel really good
about that one.

00:29:27,313 --> 00:29:28,647
I feel good. I feel good.

00:29:28,647 --> 00:29:29,982
I hope that this is gonna be
a great partnership

00:29:29,982 --> 00:29:31,116
and that, uh, Robert--

00:29:31,116 --> 00:29:33,052
The two Robert geeks
will unite

00:29:33,052 --> 00:29:36,555
to form
a-a more powerful entity.

